"Inferior mesenteric artery","Portal vein","Superior mesenteric artery","Umbilical vein"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring normal embryological development, the midgut rotates around the \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior mesenteric artery (SMA)\u003C/strong\u003E, which serves as the central axis. The process begins around week six when the midgut herniates through the umbilical ring due to rapid growth and insufficient abdominal cavity space. As the intestines return to the abdominal cavity (weeks 10-12), they complete their 270-degree counterclockwise rotation, with the duodenum moving behind the superior mesenteric artery and the caecum ultimately settling in the right iliac fossa.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The midgut undergoes physiological herniation into the umbilical cord between weeks 6-10 of development.","The superior mesenteric artery acts as the axis of rotation for midgut development.","The caecum initially develops in the upper abdomen and descends to the right iliac fossa.","Return of intestines to the abdominal cavity occurs between weeks 10-12."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51380"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15922"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51380"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-27T20:31:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T20:31:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8613"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65934"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt"